    "body": "cc @steveklabnik \n\nThis is my attempt to understand Box and Rc pointers, and especially why I should care.  I'm still learning, so I may be off the mark.  It seems to me that moving from ref -> box -> Rc -> Arc gets you progressively more flexibility (greater lifetime / size -> multiple referrers -> multiple threads) at a cost of progressively more overhead (and to a small extent, less safety: cycles of Rc pointers can leak memory).  That seems like the unifying framework and motivation.  \n\nTo understand the tradeoffs, a little Computer Systems 101 helps, so I've briefly explained the stack and heap (we don't anywhere else in the Guide).\n\nOn the issue of issue of lifetime / deallocation, I was hung up on scope, because the Guide only shows examples of lifetimes tied to scope.  But what good is a Box if it disappears when the function returns? Of course it doesn't have to (e.g. you can return boxes from functions).  The operative issue is more, well, lifetime: when you stop using it, then the compiler can free it.  I've changed the wording a little to this effect.\n\nFeedback welcome.\n",
