    "body": "I don't think the term _heap_ should occur in the documentation at all. This distinction between stack and heap memory doesn't exist in reality. Call stacks _are_ dynamic allocation just like `Box<T>` and are obtained from the operating system via the same underlying mechanism (`mmap` / `VirtualAlloc`). Local variables aren't necessarily on the call stack anyway - that's an implementation detail. The compiler will use registers as much as possible and many functions never spill to the call stack.\n\nI don't think going into low-level implementation details makes sense unless you're going to describe how things are actually implemented. The guides should stick to the semantics of the language unless someone actually wants to write accurate information about low-level implementation details / performance. The C standard manages to avoid the terms _stack_ and _heap_ completely because they really have nothing to do with language semantics (and implementations aren't that black and white anyway).\n",
